LeetCode 756 Pyramid Transition Matrix is a backtracking + memoization problem testing state definition skills—perfect for your 1690+ LC practice and OA prep.
https://leetcode.com/problems/pyramid-transition-matrix/submissions/1868761743/?envType=daily-question&envId=2025-12-29
soln video: https://youtu.be/dWlpBUZDQc0?si=3mhzTy64rCYMsPyy​

Core Concepts
State: (current_bottom_row, position_idx, partial_top_row) — all 3 needed for correct memoization
​

Transitions: From bottom[i:i+2] → possible top[i] chars via allowed rules

Base: Single char row (size==1) always valid ✓

Time: O(7^7 * 7) → memoized O(states) passes easily

Key Takeaways
cpp
// ✅ Correct memo key (your final version)
string key = bottom + "_" + to_string(idx) + "_" + top;

// ✅ Member map + clear() for multi-test
unordered_map<string,bool> memo;
memo.clear();  // Per test case

// ✅ Clean map building
mpp[s.substr(0,2)].push_back(s[2]);
Debugging Lessons
Test 61 fail: Proves top must be in memo key—different partial tops from same (bottom,idx) have different futures
​

Wrong key: (bottom,idx) only → TLE/WA on branching cases

Syntax: allowed[i][2] not allowed[2], missing ) in returns

OA Relevance
This exact pattern appears in Deshaw/FAANG OAs—row-by-row backtracking with string state memoization. Practice 5 similar (Word Ladder II, Split Array) to master.
​
